Phantom-WG Frontmatter — Architecture
=======================================

Role:
  A WSS/TLS tunnel layer placed in front of any WireGuard server
  (or UDP endpoint). Accepts WebSocket Secure connections on TCP
  443 via wstunnel, carries opaque UDP datagrams inside the
  tunnel, and delivers them to a configured backend address.

  Frontmatter is installed on a separate, dedicated server from
  the backend. Throughout this document the server running
  frontmatter is referred to as "front", and the server traffic
  is forwarded to as "backend". The two layers are not run on
  the same host.

  What a network observer on the client's side sees:
    - TCP 443, TLS handshake, traffic to front's public IP

  What a network observer on the client's side does not see:
    - The backend address
    - The WireGuard protocol fingerprint

  Contents of a .conf file:
    - Front's public host
    - wstunnel secret path prefix
    - The string 127.0.0.1:51820 (twice)

  The backend address is recorded in exactly two places on the
  front host:
    - The backend_ip row in the setup SQLite table
    - The rendered ghost-egress systemd unit file


Topology:

                                Internet
                                   |
                             TCP 443 (WSS)
                                   |
                                   v
            +------------------------------------------+
            |              Front Server                |
            |                                          |
            |   +----------------------------------+   |
            |   | wstunnel server                  |   |
            |   |   :443  (TLS termination)        |   |
            |   |   --restrict-to 127.0.0.1:51820  |   |
            |   +----------------+-----------------+   |
            |                    |                     |
            |                    v                     |
            |           127.0.0.1:51820/udp            |
            |                    |                     |
            |                    v                     |
            |   +----------------------------------+   |
            |   | egress (socat)                   |   |
            |   |   LISTEN 127.0.0.1:51820/udp     |   |
            |   |   FORWARD -> backend:<port>/udp  |   |
            |   +----------------+-----------------+   |
            |                    |                     |
            +--------------------+---------------------+
                                 |  plain UDP
                                 |  (front's own src IP)
                                 v
                       +--------------------+
                       |   Backend Server   |
                       |   (WireGuard or    |
                       |    UDP target)     |
                       +--------------------+


Packet flow:

  Client -> Front (WSS / TLS 443):
    1. The client's wstunnel opens a WSS connection to
       wss://<front_host>:443 with the secret path prefix.

    2. Front's wstunnel server validates TLS and the upgrade
       path. --restrict-to 127.0.0.1:51820 accepts only that
       destination.

    3. wstunnel decapsulates each WSS frame into a UDP datagram
       and writes it to 127.0.0.1:51820 over loopback.

  Loopback -> Backend:
    4. socat (the ghost-egress service) listens on
       127.0.0.1:51820/udp and forwards incoming datagrams to
       the backend address.

    5. The datagram leaves front's public interface. Source IP
       is front's own outbound IP.

    6. Replies trace the same path back: socat -> wstunnel ->
       WSS tunnel -> client's local 127.0.0.1:<port>.

  The backend sees front's public IP as the peer endpoint.

